05974nam a22010815i 9780228018056DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280180567 a10.1515/97802280180562doi  a(DE-B1597)655705  a(OCoLC)1350792565  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0540002bisacsh04a302.4095843qOCoLC223/eng/202303031 aKutmanaliev, Joldon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIntercommunal Warfare and Ethnic Peacemaking :bThe Dynamics of Urban Violence in Central Asia /cJoldon Kutmanaliev. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b15 figures, 1 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Protest, Power, and Resistance00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction and Theory -- tThe Puzzle and the Argument -- tExplaining Communal Violence at the Micro-Spatial Level -- tHistorical Context and the Dynamics of Violence in Osh -- tStructural-Historical Context and the Onset of Violence -- tMicrodynamics and Patterns of Violence -- tNeighbourhood-Level Comparisons -- tSpatial Security during Communal Violence in Osh -- tIntragroup Balance of Power and Self-Policing in Osh Neighbourhoods -- tSecurity Dilemma and the Variation in Neighbourhood Responses to Uncertainty in Jalalabat -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith increasing urban population density, conflicts in cities erupt more frequently and violently. Cities have become hotspots for armed combat, highlighting the urgency of understanding the impact of local communities and urban factors on the development of violent conflict. Joldon Kutmanaliev presents a novel approach to analyzing communal violence and armed conflicts in urban zones. Drawing from fieldwork in cities of southern Kyrgyzstan, he explains local-level variations in violence across neighbourhoods during the most intense and violent episode of urban communal violence in Central Asia – the clashes between Kyrgyz and Uzbeks in June 2010. Kutmanaliev explains why armed violence affects some urban neighbourhoods but not others, why local communities react differently to the same existential threat, how they deal with a deteriorating security environment and interethnic fears, and how different types of urban planning and urban landscapes influence the spread of violence. Importantly, the book identifies key factors that help local communities and their leaders to negotiate non-aggression pacts and control local constituencies, and therefore successfully prevent violence.Intercommunal Warfare and Ethnic Peacemaking explains communal war and ethnic peacemaking on the level of neighbourhood communities – a perspective that is largely absent in previous studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 70(DE-588)4019956-30(DE-627)1063197520(DE-576)208931368aGemeinde2gnd 70(DE-588)4041030-40(DE-627)1062207800(DE-576)209043172aNachbarschaft2gnd 70(DE-588)4056723-00(DE-627)1061539190(DE-576)209118741aStadt2gnd 70(DE-588)4137568-30(DE-627)1056490740(DE-576)209678720aBewaffneter Konflikt2gnd 70(DE-588)4169999-30(DE-627)1043929750(DE-576)209926821aMinderheitenfrage2gnd 70(DE-588)4195351-40(DE-627)1052125390(DE-576)210100508aLokalisation2gnd 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh  aAsian.  aKyrgyz.  aKyrgyzstan.  aOsh.  aUzbek.  aanalysis.  aarmed.  abalance.  abrokerage.  abrokers.  abuilt.  acities.  acivil.  acollective.  acommunal.  acommunity.  acomparative.  aconflict.  adi